  accentWord="Steelwork"
  subhead="You are welding connections on a mezzanine when a developer calls about a structural steel package for a commercial refit. A text goes out in five seconds — the contract stays warm."
  scenario="It is 2pm on a Friday in February. Your team has been erecting a mezzanine frame in a Banbury warehouse since 7am — 6 columns bolted to base plates on the existing slab, 12 primary beams connected at the column heads, secondary beams at 1.2-metre centres supporting composite decking, and the staircase frame bolted to the mezzanine edge beam. By 2pm the last secondary beam is being craned into position. Five missed calls between 10am and 2pm. Without Missed Call Text Back, you check at 3pm: five unknowns, one voicemail — 'call me about some steelwork' — four permanently lost. With Missed Call Text Back, all five received texts. Reply one: 'developer — new warehouse portal frame, 20m span, 7m eaves, 5 bays, Witney, 75 tonnes, need pricing in 2 weeks.' Reply two: 'builder in Headington — pair of RSJs for a rear extension, engineer's spec attached.' Reply three: 'architect — exposed steel canopy for a restaurant entrance, feature finish, about 3 tonnes.' Reply four: 'farm manager near Woodstock — replacement purlin system for a cattle building, 15 purlins rusted through.' Reply five: 'commercial landlord — loading bay canopy, 8m span, galvanised, Abingdon.' Five leads. Five distinct steelwork projects from a 75-tonne warehouse to fifteen replacement purlins. Saturday morning you prioritise the warehouse developer and the restaurant architect."
  benefits={benefits}
